President Obama has designated new national monuments that preserve important chapters of American history, including the Civil War and the civil rights movement. These monuments commemorate the Reconstruction Era, the civil rights movement in Birmingham, and the Freedom Riders who fought against segregation and violence. The President has also focused on inclusivity by designating monuments like the Stonewall National Monument for the LGBT movement and the Belmont-Paul Women's Equality National Monument for women's equality. Furthermore, he has expanded protected areas in Oregon and California to preserve natural resources and landscapes for future generations. Overall, these actions aim to ensure the preservation and celebration of American history, as well as the protection of the country's outdoors for everyone to enjoy.